@node Introduction "Stega: About Steganography and Stega"

- Steganography

Steganography is the process of hiding one thing inside of another.
The purpose of this is to transmit information without people knowing
you are doing so by placing the important/secret information inside
something innocuous.

Steganography isn't the same as cryptography, as the security of a
steganographicaly transmited message lies in people's ignorance of its
existance.  However, the two can and should be used in tandem.
Encrypting a message prior to hiding it will make sure that if someone
does find it, they won't be able to read it.  But why bother to hide it
if you have strong encryption?  Well, sometimes the people in power, be
they the government or an employer, don't like it when those under them
communicate in a way that they can't easily pry into.  Even if the 
information being sent is harmless to them, or just plain none of their
business, they will still place a burden of guilt on the sender for
acting covertly.  If those same people couldn't care less about someone
sending pictures of Cindy Crawford, samples from Monty Python, or other
types of ubiquitous net-noise, then by hiding the transmission inside
those things a person could conduct their business without being
bothered by someone else's power trip.

- How Stega Works

Stega uses the Least Significant Bits (LSB) in sound samples and true
color images to hide the bits of a message.

The LSB is the binary equivalent of the ones place.  Just as the ones
place is less significant to the overall value of a decimal number than
the tens or hundreds place, so too is the LSB not as significant as the
other bits in a binary number.  Changing the value of the LSB will only
change the overall value of the number by 1.  In an 8-bit number, which
can have a value from 0-255, changing the LSB will change the overall
value by only 1/256th.  For most things we preceive, a difference of
1/256th is just too small to notice.

Lets say we have 3 pixels from a 24-bit picture:

     RED    GREEN     BLUE       PIXEL COLOR
  --------------------------------------------
  11111111 00000000 00000000  -  Red
  11111111 11111111 11111111  -  White
  00000000 00000000 11111111  -  Blue

Notice that the pixels are made up of three 8-bit numbers, one each for
the red, green, and blue color values.  The LSB is the right-most bit.
Now, we want to hide the letter 'A' inside those pixels.  To do that we
take each bit of the character (ASCII characters are made up of 8-bits)
and place them, one-by-one, inside the LSBs of the color registers for
each pixel:

  A = 65 = 01000001

  11111110 00000001 00000000  -  Redish
  11111110 11111110 11111110  -  Whiteish
  00000000 00000001 11111111  -  Blueish

We end up with pixels who's colors are very close to the original, so
close your eye wouldn't notice the difference in most situations.

[Note that this will only work with 24-bit color and 8-bit grey scale
images since enough gradations of color/greyness are needed in order
for the change to be unnoticable.]

This works the same for sound samples (it's just easier to illustrate
with images.)  In an 8-bit sample, each sample is made up of 8 bits
(duh) and has a LSB.  The value of a sample represents the volume
of the sound at a given point in time and a 1/256th difference in
volume is hard for the human ear to hear.

- Technical Notes

The size of the message is hidden with the message for use when
extracting.  It is converted into three bytes and hidden inside the
carrier just as the message bytes are.

To get the size of the message, take the first 3 extracted bytes and use
the following formula:

   size (in bytes) = byte1 + (byte2 * 256) + (byte3 * 65536)

[Note this allows for a message size up to 16.7 million bytes.]

@endnode

