@endnode

@node Car "Stega: Carriers"

For lack of a better name, the thing in which you hide a message is
called the carrier.  Stega currently is known to support only the
following types of carrier:

 · Sound samples
   - IFF-8SVX 8-bit
   - RIFF-WAVE 8/16-bit (Windows .WAV files)
 · Images
   - uncompressed 24-bit IFF-ILBM
   - IFF-DEEP

Stega might work with some other types of IFF file formats, but it
doesn't yet support compression.  Stega looks for a BODY chunk in
the IFF file and starts doing it's thing there, so if a format
doesn't have a BODY chunk it won't work.

@endnode

@node Hint "Stega: Hints & Tips"

CONVERTING CARRIER:

 You can convert the carrier to and from different file formats
 (8SVX to WAV, WAV to .au, DEEP to ILBM, etc.) and the message will
 remain intact.

 NOTE: this is only true for LOSSLESS file formats.  JPEG and MPEG
 and other LOSSY (is that a word?) formats will remove subtlety
 (ie your message) and as such are unsuitable.

 To extract the message from the converted carrier, you will need
 to convert it to a supported file format if it isn't so already.
 example:

 8SVX + message = 8SVX(message) -> WAV(message) = WAV + message

HIDING ENCRYPTED MESSAGES:

 Since the output of encryption programs such as PGP usually have
 headers and other information attached that let the program know
 that it is an encrypted file, detecting encrypted messages hiden
 in carriers is only a matter of searching for that header info,
 something that a script could do automatically (this is also
 generally true for any situation where someone has a bit of the
 unhidden message.)  To make your encrypted messages easier to
 hide, use some method that will remove the headers.

 One program that will do this for PGP output is called Stealth
 by Henry Hastur, which is available on Unix, PCs and Amigas
 (maybe more... the version I have, v1.0, is from 1994.)  Good
 luck trying to find it, since the author didn't include any
 address to reach him (hmmmm...  sounds familiar :)

@endnode

@node Mess "Stega: Messages"

A message is whatever you want to hide.  It may be text, data, an
executable program, or anything else made up of bits (this means
things such as elephants and soap aren't legal messages, sorry.)

@endnode

@node Use "Stega: Usage"

USAGE: Stega [-<options>] <command> <carrier> [<message>] [destination]

 COMMANDS:

   H - @{" Hide " link Hide}
   X - @{" Extract " link Ext}
   V - @{" View " link View}

 OPTIONS:

   q - Quiet: don't print any disgnostic information.

 CARRIER:

   Complete path of @{" Carrier " link Car}.

 MESSAGE:

   Complete path of @{" Message " link Mess}.

 DESTINATION:

   Default destination is "RAM:encrypt" when hiding and "RAM:decrypt"
   when extracting.

@endnode

@node Hide "Stega: Hiding"

The Hide command is used to hide a message inside a carrier.

 Example usage:

   Stega h Sounds:Bevis Work:text/MySecretPlan RAM:Bevis

   - Hides the file "Work:text/MySecretPlan" inside "Sounds:Bevis"
     and saves to "RAM:Bevis".

   Stega h Sounds:Butthead c:MyProgram

   - Hides the program "c:MyProgram" inside "Sounds:Butthead" and
     saves to the default destination "RAM:encrypt".

@endnode

@node Ext "Stega: Extraction"

The Extract command is used to read a message from a carrier and save
it to a file.

 Example usage:

   Stega x Sounds:Butthead c:MyProgram

   - extracts the message from "Sounds:Butthead" and saves it to the
     file "c:MyProgram"

   Stega x RAM:Bevis

   - extracts the message from "RAM:Bevis" and saves it to the default
     destination "RAM:decrypt".

@endnode

@node View "Stega: Viewing"

The View command prints the hiden message to the shell from which Stega
was run.  It is also possible to use a pipe to redirect the output to
a printer.

View should only be used for text messages.  Using it with binary
mesages will result in garbage being printed and probably a system beep
or two.  Although harmless, this is annoying and should be avoided.

 Example usage:

   Stega v RAM:Screams

   - Reads hidden text in file "RAM:Screams" and displays in the shell.

   Stega -q v Work:GenericMPython > PRT:

   - Reads hidden text in file "Work:GenericMPython" and sends it to
     the printer without any diagnostic information (-q).

@endnode

@node Future "Stega: Future"

- Support for compressed formats
- support for DEMs (Digital Elevation Maps) if possible

@endnode

@node Bugs "Stega: Bugs & Limitations"

BUGS:
 - none yet known

LIMITS:
 - no support for compression

@endnode

@node History "Stega: History"
1.0b - initial release
1.01 - added RIFF-WAVE compatability
     - recognizes weather or not an ILBM is compressed
       (still won't use compressed ones, though)
     - general cleaning up of the IFF/RIFF parsing code
1.02 - fixed problem with the encoding of the message size
       Wouldn't work properly with sizes 512 <> 256
     - Another problem with message size fixed... It is now
       not quite compatable with earlier releases. DANG!  Oh
       well... it works better now.
     - changed command names (encrypt=hide, decrypt=extract,
       read=view.) so that it makes more sense.  Old commands
       still work (EDR).
     - created AmigaGuide documentation
1.03 - added IFF-DEEP compatability
@endnode

